04817nam a22007095i 9780231545839DE-B159720190326051319.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190326s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315458397 a10.7312/loth174662doi  a(DE-B1597)493808  a(OCoLC)1046610305  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHG181 7aBUS0270002bisacsh 7aBUS0680002bisacsh 7aBUS0690302bisacsh 7aLAW0090002bisacsh04a332.09731 aLothian, Tamara, eauthor.10aLaw and the Wealth of Nations :bFinance, Prosperity, and Democracy /cTamara Lothian. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Note Regarding the Circumstance in Which This Book Is Published -- tIntroduction -- tChapter one The Past and Future of American Finance Seen Through the Lens of Crisis -- tChapter two The Past and Future of Financial Reform: From Regulation to Reorganization -- tChapter three The Democratized Market Economy -- tChapter four The Democratized Market Economy in Latin America (and Elsewhere): An Exercise in Institutional Thinking Within Law and Political Economy -- tChapter five Economic Progress and Structural Vision -- tAppendix Crisis, Slump, Superstition, and Recovery: Thinking and Acting Beyond Vulgar Keynesianism / rLothian, Tamara / Unger, Roberto Mangabeira -- tNotes -- tIndex  aEconomic stagnation, financial crisis, and increasing inequality have provoked worldwide debate about the reshaping of the market economy. But few are willing to risk a reorientation of dominant ideas and a reform of entrenched structures. Right-wing populism has stepped into the void created by a failure to imagine structural alternatives. Tamara Lothian offers a deeper view showing the path to the reconstruction of the economy in the service of both growth and inclusion. She probes the institutional innovations that would reignite economic growth by democratizing the market. Progressives have traditionally focused only on the demand side of the economy, abandoning the supply side to conservatives. Law and the Wealth of Nations offers a progressive approach to the supply side of the economy and proposes innovation in our fundamental economic arrangements.Lothian begins by exploring how finance can serve broad-based economic growth rather than serving only itself. She goes on to show how the reform of finance can lead into the democratization of the economy. How, she asks, can we ensure that the most advanced, knowledge-intensive practices of production spread throughout the economy rather than remaining in the hands of the entrepreneurial and technological elite? How can we anchor greater economic equality and empowerment in the way we organize the economy rather than just trying to diminish inequalities after the fact by progressive taxation and entitlements? How can we revise legal thought and economic theory to develop the intellectual equipment that these tasks require? Law and the Wealth of Nations will appeal to all who are searching for ways to think practically about change in our economic and political institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2019) 0aCapital marketxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aFinancezUnited States. 0aFinancial criseszUnited States. 0aFinancial institutionsxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aLAW / Business & Financial.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311054330840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/loth17466423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231545839.jpg  aPDA5EBK  a978-3-11-054330-8  CUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL